Date: 0/0/1998
Source: Era of the Bush Trams in NZ, The
Author: MAHONEY
Vol / Page: 21
Edition:
Quote: 'The skids' were the place where logs were loaded onto a bush tram. They were constructed of a parallel row of straight logs laid on the ground and levelled. They were large enough in extent to at least store a complete train-load of logs. They were also called the bank, or the log bank, perhaps in the sense of loading bank.
